  "text": "2. Each element a has $n_{i}\\mathrm{i}\\mathrm{t}\\mathrm{h}$ associates, the number $n_{i}$ being ind epedent of $\\alpha$ . [CITATION_1] . If any two elements a and $\\beta$ are $\\mathrm{i}\\mathrm{t}\\mathrm{h}$ associates, then the number of elements that are $j\\mathrm{t}\\mathrm{h}$ associates of $\\alpha$ , and $k\\mathrm{t}\\mathrm{h}$ associates of $\\beta$ , is $p_{jk}^{l}$ and is independent of the pair of $\\mathrm{i}\\mathrm{t}\\mathrm{h}$ associates $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ .",
